From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: AAC6 HPC ops <hpc-ops@example.invalid>
Date: Fri, 8 May 2026 19:30:00 -0500
Subject: [PATCH] [timemory] tim::unwind::find_address_in_section: null-check
 _inp and section before dereferencing

bfd_map_over_sections is the canonical way to walk a bfd's sections; it
calls a user-supplied callback once per section. In a single-threaded
context the section pointer is always non-null, but the BFD library is
not thread-safe and the v1.3.0 backtrace path can drive concurrent
section iteration when several worker threads simultaneously throw
exceptions whose constructor (rocprofsys::exception<...>::exception)
captures a stack trace.  Under our reproducer (PyTorch DataLoader
post-fork + MIOpen autograd workers + a thread_data overflow throwing
out_of_range from many threads at once) this surfaces as SIGSEGV at
small near-NULL faulting addresses (0x3b4, 0x402, 0x489, ...) where
the next bfd_section_flags(section) dereferences either NULL or a
stale-pointer offset.

Adding a null-check at the top of find_address_in_section turns those
crashes into a no-op for the affected stack frame; the worst case is
that the addr2line report is incomplete for that one address, which is
strictly better than crashing with a confusing SIGSEGV that masks the
real upstream bug.

This is a defence-in-depth fix; the upstream callers should still avoid
concurrent BFD iteration.
---
 .../external/timemory/source/timemory/unwind/addr2line.cpp | 14 ++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 14 insertions(+)

--- a/projects/rocprofiler-systems/external/timemory/source/timemory/unwind/addr2line.cpp
+++ b/projects/rocprofiler-systems/external/timemory/source/timemory/unwind/addr2line.cpp
@@ -54,6 +54,20 @@
     if(!data)
         return;
 
+    // CHERRY-PICK / LOCAL FIX (rocm-7.2.x stack only):
+    // bfd_map_over_sections can hand us a NULL or stale section pointer
+    // when called from a multi-threaded backtrace path (e.g. when MIOpen
+    // worker threads spawned by torch::autograd concurrently throw
+    // exceptions whose ctors capture a backtrace through BFD, which is
+    // not thread-safe in v1.3.0). Without this guard a NULL section
+    // turns the next bfd_section_flags() into a SIGSEGV at small
+    // near-NULL addresses (0x3b4 / 0x402 / 0x489 etc).  The mainline
+    // workaround is to fix the upstream caller (do not throw exceptions
+    // on hot paths, do not enter BFD concurrently); this guard is a
+    // belt-and-braces fallback that is harmless when section is valid.
+    if(!_inp || !section)
+        return;
+
     auto* _info = static_cast<addr2line_info*>(data);
     if(*_info)
         return;
-- 
